                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       State Bank in great nick
  - Local financial giants present study in contrast      OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Bhatt in New Delhi on Monday. Picture by Ramakant Kushwaha                                        
	New Delhi, Oct. 27: The State Bank of India (SBI) today reported a 40 per cent increase in net profit for the July-September quarter at Rs 2,259.72 crore.        
	Chairman .P. Bhatt attributed the good show to high growth in interest income. He said the bank might review lending and deposit rates after a month. Bhatt expected interest rates to moderate in the coming months.        
	Net interest margin, a measure of lending profitability, widened to 3.16 per cent from 3.01 per cent a year ago.         
	Total income rose 26.41 per cent to Rs 27,083.47 crore for the quarter under review from Rs 21,424.26 crore in the year-ago period. For the six-month period ended September 30, the bank reported a consolidated net profit of Rs 4,138.06 crore, while its total income stood at Rs 50,830.90 crore.        
	Capital adequacy ratio of the bank was 12.14 per cent under Basel I norms and 11.51 per cent under Basel II. Basel norms are prudential accounting rules for banks, fixed by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision, whose members come from the developed countries.                                                                                                                                      
